<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>The KKK's revival in the 1920s was marked by:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Support for civil rights</option>
            <option letter="b">Expanded targets including immigrants and Catholics</option>
            <option letter="c">Opposition to Protestant values</option>
            <option letter="d">Promotion of racial equality</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The KKK's 1920s revival expanded its targets beyond African Americans to include immigrants, Catholics, Jews, and others perceived as threatening "traditional" American values. This broader focus reflected post-WWI nativism and cultural anxieties. The organization gained millions of members nationwide and significant political influence before declining due to internal scandals and public opposition.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
